---
import TheLeagueLayout from '../../layouts/TheLeagueLayout.astro';
---

<TheLeagueLayout title="AI Insights Corpus | The League">
  <main class="insights-page">

    <!-- ===== HERO ===== -->
    <header class="insights-hero">
      <div class="insights-hero__eyebrow">
        <span class="insights-tag">Development Knowledge Base</span>
        <span class="insights-dot">·</span>
        <span class="insights-hero__date">Jan 2026 – Present</span>
      </div>

      <h1 class="insights-hero__title">Most AI systems forget what they learn.<br>This one writes it down.</h1>

      <p class="insights-hero__deck">
        A structured corpus of hard-won knowledge accumulated across every development session.
        API quirks discovered the painful way. Design patterns refined through iteration.
        Architecture decisions documented before the rationale evaporated. Loaded into context
        at the start of every task so the machine doesn't have to rediscover the same pothole twice.
      </p>

      <div class="insights-hero__stack">
        <span class="insights-stack-item">Design System</span>
        <span class="insights-stack-dot">·</span>
        <span class="insights-stack-item">Frontend Patterns</span>
        <span class="insights-stack-dot">·</span>
        <span class="insights-stack-item">MFL API Quirks</span>
        <span class="insights-stack-dot">·</span>
        <span class="insights-stack-item">Feature Architecture</span>
        <span class="insights-stack-dot">·</span>
        <span class="insights-stack-item">Accessibility</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <!-- ===== STATS STRIP ===== -->
    <div class="insights-stats">
      <div class="insights-stats__item">
        <div class="insights-stats__value">4</div>
        <div class="insights-stats__label">Domain knowledge files</div>
      </div>
      <div class="insights-stats__item">
        <div class="insights-stats__value">8</div>
        <div class="insights-stats__label">Feature insight files</div>
      </div>
      <div class="insights-stats__item">
        <div class="insights-stats__value">35+</div>
        <div class="insights-stats__label">Individual insights recorded</div>
      </div>
      <div class="insights-stats__item">
        <div class="insights-stats__value">0</div>
        <div class="insights-stats__label">Times the same mistake was made twice</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="insights-body">

      <!-- ===== 01: HOW IT WORKS ===== -->
      <section class="insights-section">
        <div class="insights-section-header">
          <span class="insights-section-num">00</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="insights-section-title">The System</h2>
            <p class="insights-section-sub">How accumulated knowledge becomes a development accelerant</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="insights-prose">
          <p>
            Every development session produces discoveries. A third-party API that silently returns
            stale data during the offseason. A CSS token that renders fine on the design system
            demo but breaks in every real component. A drag-and-drop library that will not work
            if you wrap its items in a <code>&lt;div&gt;</code> instead of a
            <code>React.Fragment</code>. Left undocumented, these discoveries evaporate — and
            the next session rediscovers them from scratch.
          </p>
          <p>
            The AI Insights System is a structured corpus organized into files by domain
            (<code>design-system.md</code>, <code>mfl-api.md</code>, <code>frontend.md</code>)
            and by feature (<code>nav-redesign.md</code>, <code>custom-rankings.md</code>).
            Before any development task begins, relevant files are loaded into the AI's context.
            After each task completes, new learnings are written back. The knowledge compounds.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="insights-flow">
          <div class="insights-flow__node insights-flow__node--start">Task begins</div>
          <div class="insights-flow__arrow">→</div>
          <div class="insights-flow__node">Load domain + feature files into context</div>
          <div class="insights-flow__arrow">→</div>
          <div class="insights-flow__node">Execute with accumulated knowledge</div>
          <div class="insights-flow__arrow">→</div>
          <div class="insights-flow__node insights-flow__node--end">Write new learnings back</div>
          <div class="insights-flow__loop">↺ compounds across sessions</div>
        </div>

        <blockquote class="insights-quote">
          "The AI Insights System is itself a demonstration of the same principles applied
          to the product: structured context, explicit formats, and a maintained feedback loop.
          The development workflow is the feature."
        </blockquote>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 01: DESIGN SYSTEM ===== -->
      <section class="insights-section">
        <div class="insights-section-header">
          <span class="insights-section-num">01</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="insights-section-title">Design System</h2>
            <p class="insights-section-sub">Tokens, visual patterns, and the editorial language derived from the PlayerDetailsModal</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="insights-prose">
          <p>
            The design system grew bottom-up from a single modal component. The PlayerDetailsModal
            established a typographic and spatial language so coherent that it became the canonical
            reference for every page that followed. Most of what's documented here is "what
            the modal taught us" — and what had to be written down to survive the next refactor.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="insights-grid">

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Mar 1, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Design</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Editorial Design Standard</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              The left-border accent on uppercase section titles is the most recognizable
              editorial pattern in the codebase. Every new page must use it.
              The modal-derived typographic hierarchy — five distinct roles from 0.625rem
              table headers to 1.35rem hero titles — is now the site standard.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__code">
              <code>.section-title &#123; border-left: 2px solid var(--color-primary); padding-left: 0.625rem; &#125;</code>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Mar 1, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Design</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Button &amp; CTA Hierarchy (Official)</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              Dark blue (<code>#1c497c</code>) is the primary CTA. Green (<code>#2e8743</code>) is
              reserved only for affirmative/go actions like submitting a bid or confirming
              a roster change — not general-purpose CTAs. Ghost buttons pair with primary buttons,
              never solo.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              Use <code>&lt;a href&gt;</code> for navigation, <code>&lt;button&gt;</code> for
              in-page actions. Same CSS classes, different elements. Never use <code>&lt;a&gt;</code>
              without an <code>href</code>.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Mar 2, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Design</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Broadcast Diagonal Cut (Flair Pattern)</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              ESPN/FOX-inspired parallelogram clip-path for hero sections that need sports-forward
              energy. Both edges use an identical 20% horizontal slope — creating true parallel
              lines that convey motion. Primary-blue accent stripes run along each diagonal edge
              via pseudo-elements.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              One per page maximum. Hide below 767px — the geometry doesn't scale to narrow viewports.
              Used in the Free Agents hero (<code>players.astro</code>).
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Mar 2, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Design</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Negative State: Subtle Accents, Not Color Floods</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              Negative/warning states use a red left-border accent (<code>border-left: 3px solid var(--color-error)</code>)
              and red text on key values. Never use large colored backgrounds or gradient fills.
              The gray-50 card background stays neutral — the accent does all the signaling.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__code">
              <code>/* ❌ Not this */ background: var(--color-error-light);<br>/* ✓ This */ border-left: 3px solid var(--color-error);</code>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Mar 2, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Design</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">WCAG Contrast Correction: gray-400 vs gray-500</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              <code>--color-gray-400</code> (#9ca3af, ~2.86:1 contrast) fails WCAG AA for text.
              Labels, hints, and any readable text must use <code>--color-gray-500</code>
              (#6b7280, ~4.63:1) or darker. Reserve gray-400 for decorative borders and
              disabled controls only.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              This was a widespread issue. Audit any component that used gray-400 as a text color.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Jan 18, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Design</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Nav Tokens Must Live in tokens.css</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              Nav CSS variables defined only in <code>_nav-tokens.scss</code> fail on pages that
              import <code>tokens.css</code> but not the full compiled SCSS bundle.
              All <code>--nav-*</code> tokens must be defined in both files — <code>tokens.css</code>
              is the canonical source, SCSS is a mirror.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              Always include fallback values in component CSS as defensive coding:
              <code>var(--nav-team-logo-size, 40px)</code>.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Mar 1, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Design</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Modal Shell Spec (for new modals)</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              Overlay: <code>rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.45)</code> + <code>backdrop-filter: blur(2px)</code>.
              Modal: <code>max-width: 580px</code>, entry animation 0.32s ease-out with
              scale(0.96→1) + translateY. Mobile: bottom-sheet slide-up with top-only radius.
              Close button: 32px circle, absolute top-right.
            </p>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 02: FRONTEND PATTERNS ===== -->
      <section class="insights-section">
        <div class="insights-section-header">
          <span class="insights-section-num">02</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="insights-section-title">Frontend Patterns</h2>
            <p class="insights-section-sub">Component architecture, player display, headshots, and the gotchas that cost real time</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="insights-prose">
          <p>
            Frontend work in this codebase has a consistent source of friction: third-party
            data that doesn't quite match what you expect, and small normalization gaps that
            produce broken logos or missing headshots for specific teams. The Player Lockup
            standard exists because every component that skipped it eventually had broken
            Kansas City Chiefs logos.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="insights-grid">

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Feb 23, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Frontend</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Player Lockup Standard (and why it exists)</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              Multiple components had slightly different player display patterns — some missed
              DEF handling, some skipped <code>normalizeTeamCode()</code>. The result: broken
              logos for KCC (file is KC.svg), JAC, NEP, NOS, and DEF players showing a generic
              silhouette instead of the team logo.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              Always use <code>PlayerCell.astro</code> or <code>buildPlayerCellHTML()</code>.
              Test with Kansas City, Jacksonville, New England, and New Orleans. DEF handling
              is automatic — don't special-case it.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Mar 1, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Frontend</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">ESPN Headshot URLs + College Fallback Chain</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              ESPN uses different athlete IDs for college and NFL — a player's college athlete ID
              is NOT the same as their NFL player ID. MFL stores ESPN NFL IDs as <code>espn_id</code>
              but 2026 draft prospects have none. College headshots require a separate mapping file
              (<code>data/theleague/espn-college-ids.json</code>).
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__code">
              <code>ESPN NFL → ESPN College → MFL headshot → placeholder</code>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Feb 12, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Frontend</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Franchise History for Name/Logo Changes</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              Heavy Chevy rebranded to Dead Cap Walking for 2026. Historical views need to show
              "Heavy Chevy" for 2024 data. A <code>history[]</code> array in
              <code>theleague.config.json</code> with <code>yearStart</code>/<code>yearEnd</code>
              plus all identity fields solves this via <code>getTeamIdentityForYear()</code>.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              Pages showing historical data must use <code>getTeamIdentityForYear(team, year)</code>
              from <code>src/utils/team-names.ts</code>. Future rebrands only need a new
              history entry in config.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Jan 18, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Frontend</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Dark Mode: Both Media Query AND .dark Class</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              All new components must support dark mode via two mechanisms:
              <code>@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)</code> for OS-level preference,
              and <code>.dark</code> class on <code>:root</code> for a manual toggle.
              Use <code>:global(.dark)</code> in Astro scoped styles to target the class.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Mar 2, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Frontend</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Clean URL Rewrites Break on Prerendered Pages</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              Host-level clean URL rewrites (<code>/trade-builder</code> →
              <code>/theleague/trade-builder</code>) depend on runtime route resolution in
              <code>middleware.ts</code>. Pages with <code>prerender = true</code> only exist as
              static output and don't register as runtime route entries — the middleware rewrite
              cannot resolve them.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              Any TheLeague page linked from the nav drawer must use <code>prerender = false</code>
              while clean URL rewriting is active. Affected pages: calendar, league-summary,
              trade-builder, import-rankings.
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 03: MFL API ===== -->
      <section class="insights-section">
        <div class="insights-section-header">
          <span class="insights-section-num">03</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="insights-section-title">MFL API Quirks</h2>
            <p class="insights-section-sub">Third-party API behavior that is not documented, not obvious, and not forgiving</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="insights-prose">
          <p>
            MyFantasyLeague's API is mature but idiosyncratic. Most of what's documented here
            is behavior that only becomes visible under specific conditions — the pre-rollover
            window, a serverless execution environment, a league with a non-standard
            <code>draftPlayerPool</code> setting. The notes exist so these conditions don't
            produce mysterious failures that take hours to trace.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="insights-grid">

          <div class="insights-card insights-card--wide">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Feb 26, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">MFL API</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Login Authentication: XML, Not JSON</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              The MFL login endpoint does NOT support <code>JSON=1</code> — it returns an
              empty body. Use <code>XML=1</code> instead. The response is XML:
              <code>&lt;status MFL_USER_ID="base64cookie"/&gt;</code> on success,
              <code>&lt;error&gt;Invalid Password&lt;/error&gt;</code> on failure.
              The standalone <code>/myleagues</code> endpoint always returns HTML from
              server-side fetch — use <code>export?TYPE=myleagues&amp;JSON=1</code> instead.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__code">
              <code>
                Step 1: POST /login?XML=1 → parse XML for MFL_USER_ID<br>
                Step 2: GET /export?TYPE=myleagues&amp;JSON=1 with Cookie: MFL_USER_ID=…
              </code>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card insights-card--wide">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Feb 13–14, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">MFL API</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Rosters API Staleness During Pre-Rollover Window</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              Between season end and the Feb 14 league year rollover, the <code>rosters</code>
              endpoint can return stale data for recent drops — confirmed 31+ hours after
              drops occurred. The <code>transactions</code> and <code>freeAgents</code> endpoints
              correctly reflected changes. The <code>rosters</code> endpoint is not the sole
              source of truth during the offseason.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              During the offseason, cross-reference <code>rosters</code> with recent
              <code>TRANS_TYPE=FREE_AGENT</code> transactions. Filter out players in
              drop-only transactions (<code>|&#123;id&#125;,</code> format). Transaction endpoint requires
              following HTTP 302 redirects — use <code>-L</code> or a redirect-following client.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Feb 27, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">MFL API</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">myWatchList vs myDraftList</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              <code>myDraftList</code> is ordered but destructive (complete overwrite) and
              possibly restricted to <code>draftPlayerPool</code> players.
              <code>myWatchList</code> supports incremental ADD/REMOVE and has no documented
              player restrictions — but is unordered (a set, not a ranked list).
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              For custom rankings: use <code>myWatchList</code> as the MFL-synced "flagged"
              set. Store ranking order in Upstash Redis or local storage.
              Use <code>playerRanks</code> (FantasySharks) as the default seed.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Feb 24, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">MFL API</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">pointsAllowed: Full Season Only, Strings Not Numbers</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              The <code>pointsAllowed</code> DVP endpoint accepts a <code>W</code> (week) param
              but completely ignores it — all requests return identical full-season cumulative
              totals. Point values are strings — always <code>parseFloat()</code> before math.
              MFL uses non-standard team codes (KCC, JAC, NEP) — always <code>normalizeTeamCode()</code>.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              For weekly DVP context, combine with <code>nflSchedule</code>. For season-long
              averages, divide by 17. Filter out entries with <code>name: ""</code>.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Feb 12, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">MFL API</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">No Dedicated Franchise History API</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              MFL has no endpoint for franchise name/logo history. The year-specific
              <code>league</code> export returns names as they were that year.
              Pre-2016 seasons used different league IDs (e.g., 2007: <code>76273</code>
              on www42) — all mapped in the <code>history.league</code> array of the
              current year's league data.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              Project advantage: <code>data/theleague/mfl-feeds/&#123;YEAR&#125;/league.json</code>
              is cached for 2011–2025. No additional API calls needed for historical names.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Feb 13, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">MFL API</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Free Agent Status "locked" in Offseason</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              Players dropped during the offseason appear in <code>freeAgents</code> with
              <code>status: "locked"</code> — they cannot be claimed until the new league
              year begins or waivers open. This is distinct from <code>status: "available"</code>
              which means claims are open.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              Display <code>status: "locked"</code> players with a visual indicator
              (grayed out or lock icon) to signal they're not claimable.
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 04: FEATURE INSIGHTS ===== -->
      <section class="insights-section">
        <div class="insights-section-header">
          <span class="insights-section-num">04</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="insights-section-title">Feature Architecture</h2>
            <p class="insights-section-sub">What building each major feature taught us about the next one</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="insights-prose">
          <p>
            Feature development is where abstract architectural decisions meet concrete
            implementation reality. The nav redesign taught us about the limits of prerendering
            and the importance of cookie-first server rendering. Custom rankings exposed
            edge cases in drag-and-drop library assumptions. Each feature's learnings
            file is a post-mortem for the next engineer.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="insights-grid">

          <div class="insights-card insights-card--wide">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Feb 28, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Custom Rankings</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">@dnd-kit: Three Silent Killers</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              Drag-and-drop simply stops working if: (1) the sortable container has
              <code>overflow: hidden</code> — dragged elements appear not to move;
              (2) <code>restrictToParentElement</code> modifier is used — constrains
              drag too aggressively; (3) sortable items are wrapped in extra
              <code>&lt;div&gt;</code>s instead of <code>React.Fragment</code> — confuses
              position tracking. All three issues can be present simultaneously and interact.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              Only use <code>restrictToVerticalAxis</code> modifier. Never add
              <code>overflow: hidden</code> to the sortable container. Use
              <code>React.Fragment</code> for item wrappers. Check
              <code>ManageImportsSection.tsx</code> for a working reference pattern.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Feb 28, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Custom Rankings</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Upstash Redis for Cross-Device KV</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              For per-user state (&lt;10KB) that needs cross-device sync without a full
              database, Upstash Redis via <code>@upstash/redis</code> is the answer.
              Auto-reads env vars (<code>UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_URL</code>, <code>UPSTASH_REDIS_REST_TOKEN</code>).
              Each request is a standalone HTTP call — no connection management.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__code">
              <code>key pattern: &#123;feature&#125;:&#123;franchiseId&#125;</code><br>
              <code>e.g. cr:0003 for franchise 0003's custom rankings</code>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Feb 28, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Custom Rankings</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Edit Mode Prevents Accidental Drag</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              @dnd-kit supports empty <code>useSensors()</code> which completely disables drag
              without unmounting the context. Passing <code>sensors=&#123;isEditing ? editSensors : noSensors&#125;</code>
              gates drag to an explicit edit mode, preventing accidental reorders while browsing
              the list.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              Mobile touch targets for hidden-on-hover UI need explicit fallbacks:
              always-visible at 0.4 opacity on mobile, full opacity on <code>:active</code>.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Feb 28, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Custom Rankings</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Composite Hash for Staleness Detection</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              When rankings derive from user-configured composite sources, a hash of the
              source config (sorted member IDs + player count) reliably detects when the
              source data changed. On mismatch, <code>mergeWithOverrides()</code> re-seeds
              from the new composite while preserving manual customizations.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              For any feature that derives from user-configured data: store a hash alongside
              the derived state. This enables automatic reconciliation without losing overrides.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Jan 18, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Nav Redesign</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">MutationObserver Beats Custom Events for State Sync</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              The page wrapper needs to respond to drawer state changes (open/close) by
              adjusting its <code>margin-right</code>. Using MutationObserver to watch for
              class changes on the drawer element is more robust than custom events — it
              catches all state changes regardless of how they were triggered, including
              programmatic changes from <code>window.navDrawer</code> API calls.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-card">
            <div class="insights-card__meta">
              <span class="insights-card__date">Jan 18, 2026</span>
              <span class="insights-card__domain">Nav Redesign</span>
            </div>
            <h3 class="insights-card__title">Playwright Surfaced Critical Spacing Issues</h3>
            <p class="insights-card__body">
              E2E testing revealed nav links were 26.59px tall instead of the 40px minimum
              touch target. SVG icons were rendering at browser default size (hundreds of pixels)
              because Astro scoped CSS wasn't targeting nested SVGs — required
              <code>:global(.nav-links__icon svg)</code> and explicit <code>width/height</code>
              attributes on the SVG element itself.
            </p>
            <div class="insights-card__rec">
              Run Playwright after any CSS changes to catch spacing/sizing regressions.
              Always add explicit <code>width</code> and <code>height</code> attributes to
              SVGs used as nav icons.
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== 05: PATTERNS THAT COMPOUND ===== -->
      <section class="insights-section">
        <div class="insights-section-header">
          <span class="insights-section-num">05</span>
          <div>
            <h2 class="insights-section-title">Patterns That Compound</h2>
            <p class="insights-section-sub">The meta-observations that emerge after enough individual insights accumulate</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="insights-prose">
          <p>
            After enough individual insights accumulate, second-order patterns start to
            emerge. These aren't observations about specific API endpoints or CSS tokens —
            they're observations about the shape of problems in this codebase.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="insights-patterns">
          <div class="insights-pattern-card">
            <div class="insights-pattern-card__num">I</div>
            <div class="insights-pattern-card__content">
              <div class="insights-pattern-card__title">Third-Party Data Is Wrong Under Specific Conditions</div>
              <p class="insights-pattern-card__body">
                MFL's rosters endpoint returns stale data in the pre-rollover window.
                ESPN's headshot CDN serves 404s for players without photos instead of
                a fallback. <code>pointsAllowed</code> ignores the week parameter silently.
                None of these are bugs in the traditional sense — they're edge conditions
                that exist at the boundaries between systems. The documentation for these
                conditions is the codebase.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-pattern-card">
            <div class="insights-pattern-card__num">II</div>
            <div class="insights-pattern-card__content">
              <div class="insights-pattern-card__title">Small Normalization Gaps Compound into Broken UX</div>
              <p class="insights-pattern-card__body">
                A missing <code>normalizeTeamCode()</code> call doesn't fail loudly —
                it silently serves a 404 for a logo file. Skipping DEF handling in a
                player component doesn't crash — it shows a generic avatar instead of
                the team logo. These failures are invisible until someone looks at the
                specific player or team that triggers them. The Player Lockup standard
                exists because every shortcut eventually produces a broken logo.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="insights-pattern-card">
            <div class="insights-pattern-card__num">III</div>
            <div class="insights-pattern-card__content">
              <div class="insights-pattern-card__title">Architecture Decisions Cost More to Change Than to Get Right</div>
              <p class="insights-pattern-card__body">
                The clean URL rewrite system requires pages to be server-rendered.
                The token system requires <code>tokens.css</code> as the canonical source.
                The franchise history system requires a <code>history[]</code> array in config
                rather than dynamic API calls. Each of these decisions has a straightforward
                rationale that is obvious in hindsight — and expensive to retrofit when
                discovered late. The insights corpus exists to make them obvious upfront.
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <blockquote class="insights-quote">
          "The best time to document a quirk is immediately after discovering it, before
          the workaround becomes load-bearing and the original problem is forgotten. The
          second best time is now."
        </blockquote>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== CLOSING ===== -->
      <section class="insights-closing">
        <div class="insights-closing__inner">
          <div class="insights-closing__text">
            <h2 class="insights-closing__title">The File Structure</h2>
            <p>
              The corpus lives in <code>docs/claude/insights/</code>. Domain files cover
              cross-cutting concerns: <code>design-system.md</code>, <code>frontend.md</code>,
              <code>mfl-api.md</code>, <code>accessibility.md</code>. Feature files cover
              the learnings specific to each major feature: <code>nav-redesign.md</code>,
              <code>custom-rankings.md</code>, and growing.
            </p>
            <p>
              Each entry follows a consistent format: date, context, insight, evidence,
              recommendation. New entries are appended, not edited — the history of how
              understanding evolved is part of the value.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="insights-closing__ctas">
            <a href="/theleague/about" class="insights-btn insights-btn--primary">
              Read the Full Case Study
              <span class="insights-btn__arrow">→</span>
            </a>
            <a href="/theleague/whats-new" class="insights-btn insights-btn--ghost">
              What's New
              <span class="insights-btn__arrow">→</span>
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

    </div><!-- /.insights-body -->
  </main>
</TheLeagueLayout>

